<dl id="s14012d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="us14" href="#s14012d">Oxen of the Sun: </a><a href="../../FF/unbs/s14all.htm#s14012d">sector 12(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Yea, nay, ay, yes, no,</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Thus the fine distinction between <mark>&lsquo;yea&rsquo; and &lsquo;yes&rsquo;, &lsquo;nay&rsquo; and &lsquo;no&rsquo;,</mark> that once existed in English, has quite disappeared. &lsquo;Yay&rsquo; and &lsquo;Nay&rsquo;, in Wiclif&apos;s time, and a good deal later, were answers to questions framed in the affirmative. <small> Richard Chenevix Trench, <a name="RCTW" href="/udra/udex.htm#RCTW"><cite title="source">An Anthology of The Study of Words</cite></a>(1851), 258n</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
